          How Cold Exposure Affects Hormones
        </h2>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Cold plunging triggers a cascade of hormonal responses that can help restore balance and improve overall endocrine function.
        </p>
        
        <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-xl text-gray-800 mb-4">Cortisol Regulation</h3>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          One of the most significant benefits of cold therapy for women is its ability to help regulate cortisol, the primary stress hormone. Chronic stress and elevated cortisol levels can disrupt the entire hormonal cascade, affecting everything from reproductive hormones to thyroid function.
        </p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          Regular cold exposure acts as a controlled stressor that trains the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal (HPA) axis to respond more efficiently to stress. Over time, this can lead to more balanced cortisol patterns and improved stress resilience.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-xl text-gray-800 mb-4">Norepinephrine and Mood Hormones</h3>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          Cold plunging dramatically increases norepinephrine levels—sometimes by 200-300%. This neurotransmitter plays crucial roles in mood regulation, focus, and energy. For women dealing with <a href="/blog/menstrual-cycle-symptoms" class="text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-800">hormonal mood swings</a>, this boost can provide natural mood stabilization.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-xl text-gray-800 mb-4">Metabolic Hormones</h3>
